{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1781683000,"nonce":"tFvtCLWGmw1B9UV8Ai7S8WleYi0=","title":"UPSERT: INSERT ... ON CONFLICT DO UPDATE / DO NOTHING","message":"There is no upsert path. Inserts go through conn.to::\u003cTable\u003e() / conn.to_columns::\u003cTable, Columns\u003e() and end in insert / insert_returning, with no ON CONFLICT clause.\n\nGiven the Postgres focus and that partial unique indexes are already modelled (the soft-delete idiom), upsert is a natural high-value addition.\n\nScope:\n- on_conflict(target) where target is a column set or a named unique/constraint, type-checked against the table derive (reuse the marker column types).\n- do_nothing() and do_update(|excluded, current| ...assignments...), where the update assignments can reference EXCLUDED.* and the existing row, mirroring the update-builder set() closure.\n- Optional WHERE on DO UPDATE.\n- Works with insert_returning.\n\nPostgres-first; MySQL has its own INSERT ... ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE shape, so the backend trait should abstract the conflict clause rather than hard-coding pg syntax.","files":null}]}